== History == The forerunner of the Gokoku Shrine, the {{ill|Shōkonsha|ja|招魂社|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shōkonsha|qq=}}, was established in various domains within {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinano Province|qq=}} to honor the war dead from the {{ill|Boshin War|ja|戊辰戦争|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Boshin War|qq=}}. These were set up in the Matsushiro, Iwamurada, and Suzaka domains in 1868 (Meiji 1). Later, additional Shōkonsha were established in Taguchi ({{ill|Okutono Domain|ja|奥殿藩|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okutono Domain|qq=}}), Kamiina ({{ill|Takato Domain|ja|高遠藩|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takato Domain|qq=}}), Suwa ({{ill|Suwa Domain|ja|諏訪藩|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suwa Domain|qq=}}), and in {{ill|Shinano|ja|信濃|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinano|qq=}} (Nagano City). To commemorate those who perished in the {{ill|First Sino-Japanese War|ja|日清戦争|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/First Sino-Japanese War|qq=}} and {{ill|Russo-Japanese War|ja|日露戦争|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Russo-Japanese War|qq=}}, plans for a prefecture-wide Shōkonsha were made in 1934 (Shōwa 9).
In November 1938 (Shōwa 13), the Nagano Prefecture Shōkonsha was established as a temporary shrine by order of Emperor Meiji to honor all soldiers who died in the Boshin War<ref name="cloud">{{cite web |url=https://readyfor.jp/projects/torii |title=台風で倒壊した長野縣護國神社の鳥居再建にお力を貸してください |work=READYFOR |accessdate=2023-06-28|en}}</ref>. It was renamed Nagano Prefecture Gokoku Shrine in March 1939 (Shōwa 14) and designated as a Gokoku Shrine by the Minister of Home Affairs on April 1 of the same year. The third verse of the Matsumoto City song, established two years after its founding in 1940 (Shōwa 15), mentions the shrine: "The shrine stands to protect the country." In 1942 (Shōwa 17), the shrine buildings, office, and three {{ill|Torii|ja|鳥居|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Torii|qq=}} gates were completed<ref name="cloud" />.
After World War II, to avoid being perceived as a militaristic facility, the shrine was temporarily renamed "Misuzu no Miya," derived from the ancient name for Shinano Province. In April 1957 (Shōwa 32), it was designated a Beppyo Shrine by the {{ill|Association of Shinto Shrines|ja|神社本庁|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Association of Shinto Shrines|qq=}}.
On May 14, 1964 (Shōwa 39), Emperor Shōwa and Empress Kōjun visited the shrine during their inspection of the prefecture for the 15th National Arbor Day<ref>{{cite book |author=Hara Takeshi |title=昭和天皇御召列車全記録 |publisher=新潮社 |year=2016-09-30 |page=126 |isbn=978-4-10-320523-4|en}}</ref>.
=== Torii Collapse === In 2017 (Heisei 29), the second torii gate collapsed during [[:en:Typhoon Lan (2017)|Typhoon Lan]]. Standing 7 meters tall and made of Taiwanese cypress, the gate's reconstruction was funded through a crowdfunding campaign on . The campaign raised ¥3,232,000, surpassing the ¥3 million goal<ref name="cloud" />. Repairs to the first torii and side torii gates were also planned, with new pillars and reused crosspieces.
In 2018 (Heisei 30), the side torii gate on the east side, also made of wood and about 6 meters tall, collapsed during {{ill|Typhoon Jebi|ja|平成30th year 台風第21号|en|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Typhoon Jebi|qq=}}<ref>{{cite news |date=2018-09-07 |url=https://www.sankei.com/article/20180905-NWSBDZ63N5LPZOUISKZE7UA7Y4/ |title=長野県護国神社で鳥居がまた倒壊 |work=産経新聞 |accessdate=2018-09-07|en}}</ref>. This required an unscheduled rebuild.
